\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\kerning0\b0\fs24\par
David Becker strode over and stared down at the old man asleep on the cot. The man's right wrist was wrapped in a cast. He was between sixty and seventy years old. His snow-white hair was parted neatly to the side, and in the center of his forehead was a deep purple welt that spread down into his right eye.\par
\i A little bump? \i0 he thought, recalling the lieutenant's words. Becker checked the man's fingers. There was no gold ring anywhere. Becker reached down and touched the man's arm. "Sir?" He shook him lightly. "Excuse me... sir?"\par
The man didn't move.\par
Becker tried again, a little louder. "Sir?"\par
The man stirred. "Qu'est-ce... quelle heure est--" He slowly opened his eyes and focused on Becker. He scowled at having been disturbed. "Qu'est-ce-que vous voulez?"\par
\i Yes, \i0 Becker thought, \i a French Canadian!\i0  Becker smiled down at him. "Do you have a moment?"\par
Although Becker's French was perfect, he spoke in what he hoped would be the man's weaker language, English. Convincing a total stranger to hand over a gold ring might be a little tricky; Becker figured he could use any edge he could get.\par
There was a long silence as the man got his bearings. He surveyed his surroundings and lifted a long finger to smooth his limp white mustache. Finally he spoke. "What do you want?" His English carried a thin, nasal accent.\par
"Sir," Becker said, over pronouncing his words as if speaking to a deaf person, "I need to ask you a few questions."\par
The man glared up at him with a strange look on his face. "Do you have some sort of problem?"\par
Becker frowned; the man's English was impeccable. He immediately lost the condescending tone. "I'm sorry to bother you, sir, but were you by any chance at the Plaza de Espa\'f1a today?"\par
The old man's eyes narrowed. "Are you from the City Council?"\par
"No, actually I'm--"\par
"Bureau of Tourism?"\par
"No, I'm--"\par
"Look, I know why you're here!" The old man struggled to sit up. "I'm not going to be intimidated! If I've said it once, I've said it a thousand times--Pierre Cloucharde writes the world the way he \i lives\i0  the world. Some of your corporate guidebooks might sweep this under the table for a free night on the town, but the \i Montreal Times\i0  is \i not\i0  for hire! I refuse!"\par
"I'm sorry, sir. I don't think you under--"\par
"Merde alors! I understand perfectly!" He wagged a bony finger at Becker, and his voice echoed through the gymnasium. "You're not the first! They tried the same thing at the Moulin Rouge, Brown's Palace, and the Golfigno in Lagos! But \i what\i0  went to press? The truth! The worst Wellington I've ever eaten! The filthiest tub I've ever seen! And the rockiest beach I've ever walked! My readers expect no less!"\par
Patients on nearby cots began sitting up to see what was going on. Becker looked around nervously for a nurse. The last thing he needed was to get kicked out.\par
Cloucharde was raging. "That miserable excuse for a police officer works for \i your\i0  city! He made me get on his motorcycle! Look at me!" He tried to lift his wrist. \i "Now\i0  who's going to write my column?"\par
"Sir, I--"\par
"I've never been so uncomfortable in my forty-three years of travel! Look at this place! You know, my column is syndicated in over--"\par
"Sir!" Becker held up both hands urgently signaling truce. "I'm not interested in your column; I'm from the Canadian Consulate. I'm here to make sure you're okay!"\par
Suddenly there was a dead quiet in the gymnasium. The old man looked up from his bed and eyed the intruder suspiciously.\par
Becker ventured on in almost a whisper. "I'm here to see if there's anything I can do to help." \i Like bring you a couple of Valium.\par
\i0 After a long pause, the Canadian spoke. "The consulate?" His tone softened considerably.\par
Becker nodded.\par
"So, you're \i not\i0  here about my column?"\par
"No, sir."\par
It was as if a giant bubble had burst for Pierre Cloucharde. He settled slowly back down onto his mound of pillows. He looked heartbroken. "I thought you were from the city... trying to get me to..." He faded off and then looked up. "If it's not about my column, then why \i are\i0  you here?"\par
It was a good question, Becker thought, picturing the Smoky Mountains. "Just an informal diplomatic courtesy," he lied.\par
The man looked surprised. "A diplomatic courtesy?"\par
"Yes, sir. As I'm sure a man of your stature is well aware, the Canadian government works hard to protect its countrymen from the indignities suffered in these, er--shall we say--less \i refined\i0  countries."\par
Cloucharde's thin lips parted in a knowing smile. "But of course... how pleasant."\par
"You \i are\i0  a Canadian citizen, aren't you?"\par
"Yes, of course. How silly of me. Please forgive me. Someone in my position is often approached with... well... you understand."\par
"Yes, Mr. Cloucharde, I certainly do. The price one pays for celebrity."\par
"Indeed." Cloucharde let out a tragic sigh. He was an unwilling martyr tolerating the masses. "Can you believe this hideous place?" He rolled his eyes at the bizarre surroundings. "It's a mockery. And they've decided to keep me overnight."\par
Becker looked around. "I know. It's terrible. I'm sorry it took me so long to get here."\par
Cloucharde looked confused. "I wasn't even aware you were coming."\par
Becker changed the subject. "Looks like a nasty bump on your head. Does it hurt?"\par
"No, not really. I took a spill this morning--the price one pays for being a good Samaritan. The wrist is the thing that's hurting me. Stupid Guardia. I mean, really! Putting a man of \i my\i0  age on a motorcycle. It's reprehensible."\par
"Is there anything I can get for you?"\par
Cloucharde thought a moment, enjoying the attention. "Well, actually..." He stretched his neck and tilted his head left and right. "I \i could\i0  use another pillow if it's not too much trouble."\par
"Not at all." Becker grabbed a pillow off a nearby cot and helped Cloucharde get comfortable.\par
The old man sighed contentedly. "Much better... thank you."\par
"Pas du tout," Becker replied.\par
"Ah!" The man smiled warmly. "So you \i do \i0 speak the language of the civilized world."\par
"That's about the extent of it," Becker said sheepishly.\par
"Not a problem," Cloucharde declared proudly. "My column is syndicated in the U.S.; my English is first rate."\par
"So I've heard." Becker smiled. He sat down on the edge of Cloucharde's cot. "Now, if you don't mind my asking, Mr. Cloucharde, why would a man such as yourself come to a place like \i this? \i0 There are far better hospitals in Seville."\par
Cloucharde looked angry. "That police officer... he bucked me off his motorcycle and then left me bleeding in the street like a stuck pig. I had to walk over here."\par
"He didn't offer to take you to a better facility?"\par
"On that godawful bike of his? No thanks!"\par
"What exactly happened this morning?"\par
"I told it all to the lieutenant."\par
"I've spoken to the officer and--"\par
"I hope you reprimanded him!" Cloucharde interrupted.\par
Becker nodded. "In the severest terms. My office will be following up."\par
"I should hope so."\par
"Monsieur Cloucharde." Becker smiled, pulling a pen out of his jacket pocket. "I'd like to make a formal complaint to the city. Would you help? A man of your reputation would be a valuable witness."\par
Cloucharde looked buoyed by the prospect of being quoted. He sat up. "Why, yes... of course. It would be my pleasure."\par
Becker took out a small note pad and looked up. "Okay, let's start with this morning. Tell me about the accident."\par
The old man sighed. "It was sad really. The poor Asian fellow just collapsed. I tried to help him--but it was no use."\par
"You gave him CPR?"\par
Cloucharde looked ashamed. "I'm afraid I don't know how. I called an ambulance."\par
Becker remembered the bluish bruises on Tankado's chest. "Did the paramedics administer CPR?"\par
"Heavens, no!" Cloucharde laughed. "No reason to whip a dead horse--the fellow was long gone by the time the ambulance got there. They checked his pulse and carted him off, leaving me with that horrific policeman."\par
\i That's strange, \i0 Becker thought, wondering where the bruise had come from. He pushed it from his mind and got to the matter at hand. "What about the ring?" he said as nonchalantly as possible.\par
Cloucharde looked surprised. "The lieutenant told you about the ring?"\par
"Yes, he did."\par
Cloucharde seemed amazed. "Really? I didn't think he believed my story. He was so rude--as if he thought I were lying. But my story was accurate, of course. I pride myself on accuracy."\par
"Where is the ring?" Becker pressed.\par
Cloucharde didn't seem to hear. He was glassy-eyed, staring into space. "Strange piece really, all those letters--looked like no language I'd ever seen."\par
"Japanese, maybe?" Becker offered.\par
"Definitely not."\par
"So you got a good look at it?"\par
"Heavens, yes! When I knelt down to help, the man kept pushing his fingers in my face. He wanted to give me the ring. It was most bizarre, horrible really--his hands were quite dreadful."\par
"And that's when you took the ring?"\par
Cloucharde went wide-eyed. "That's what the officer told you! That \i I\i0  took the ring?"\par
Becker shifted uneasily.\par
