Becker stared in shock at Roc\'edo. "You \i sold\i0  the ring?"\par
The woman nodded, her silky red hair falling around her shoulders.\par
Becker willed it not to be true. "Pero... but..."\par
She shrugged and said in Spanish, "A girl near the park."\par
Becker felt his legs go weak. \i This can't be!\i0\par
Roc\'edo smiled coyly and motioned to the German. "\'c9l quer\'eda que lo guardara. He wanted to keep it, but I told him no. I've got Gitana blood in me, Gypsy blood; we Gitanas, in addition to having red hair, are very superstitious. A ring offered by a dying man is not a good sign."\par
"Did you know the girl?" Becker interrogated.\par
Roc\'edo arched her eyebrows. "Vaya. You really want this ring, don't you?"\par
Becker nodded sternly. "Who did you sell it to?"\par
The enormous German sat bewildered on the bed. His romantic evening was being ruined, and he apparently had no idea why. "Was passiert?" he asked nervously. "What's happening?"\par
Becker ignored him.\par
"I didn't actually sell it," Roc\'edo said. "I tried to, but she was just a kid and had no money. I ended up giving it to her. Had I known about your generous offer, I would have saved it for you."\par
"Why did you leave the park?" Becker demanded. "Somebody had died. Why didn't you wait for the police? And give \i them\i0  the ring?"\par
"I solicit many things, Mr. Becker, but \i trouble\i0  is not one of them. Besides, that old man seemed to have things under control."\par
"The Canadian?"\par
"Yes, he called the ambulance. We decided to leave. I saw no reason to involve my date or myself with the police."\par
Becker nodded absently. He was still trying to accept this cruel twist of fate. \i She gave the damn thing away!\i0\par
"I tried to help the dying man," Roc\'edo explained. "But he didn't seem to want it. He started with the ring--kept pushing it in our faces. He had these three crippled fingers sticking up. He kept pushing his hand at us--like we were supposed to take the ring. I didn't want to, but my friend here finally did. Then the guy died."\par
"And you tried CPR?" Becker guessed.\par
"No. We didn't touch him. My friend got scared. He's big, but he's a wimp." She smiled seductively at Becker. "Don't worry--he can't speak a word of Spanish."\par
Becker frowned. He was wondering again about the bruises on Tankado's chest. "Did the paramedics give CPR?"\par
"I have no idea. As I told you, we left before they arrived."\par
"You mean after you \i stole\i0  the ring." Becker scowled.\par
Roc\'edo glared at him. "We did not steal the ring. The man was dying. His intentions were clear. We gave him his last wish."\par
Becker softened. Roc\'edo was right; he probably would have done the same damn thing. "But then you gave the ring to some girl?"\par
"I told you. The ring made me nervous. The girl had lots of jewelry on. I thought she might like it."\par
"And she didn't think it was strange? That you'd just \i give\i0  her a ring?"\par
"No. I told her I found it in the park. I thought she might offer to pay me for it, but she didn't. I didn't care. I just wanted to get rid of it."\par
"When did you give it to her?"\par
Roc\'edo shrugged. "This afternoon. About an hour after I got it."\par
Becker checked his watch: 11:48 p.m. The trail was eight hours old. \i What the hell am I doing here? I'm supposed to be in the Smokys. \i0 He sighed and asked the only question he could think of. "What did the girl look like?"\par
"Era un punki," Roc\'edo replied.\par
Becker looked up, puzzled. "Un punki?"\par
"S\'ed. Punki."\par
"A punk?"\par
"Yes, a punk," she said in rough English, and then immediately switched back to Spanish. "Mucha joyer\'eda. Lots of jewelry. A weird pendant in one ear. A skull, I think."\par
"There are punk rockers in Seville?"\par
Roc\'edo smiled. "Todo bajo el sol. Everything under the sun." It was the motto of Seville's Tourism Bureau.\par
"Did she give you her name?"\par
"No."\par
"Did she say where she was going?"\par
"No. Her Spanish was poor."\par
"She wasn't Spanish?" Becker asked.\par
"No. She was English, I think. She had wild hair--red, white, and blue."\par
Becker winced at the bizarre image. "Maybe she was American," he offered.\par
"I don't think so," Roc\'edo said. "She was wearing a T-shirt that looked like the British flag."\par
Becker nodded dumbly. "Okay. Red, white, and blue hair, a British flag T-shirt, a skull pendant in her ear. What else?"\par
"Nothing. Just your average punk."\par
\i Average punk? \i0 Becker was from a world of collegiate sweatshirts and conservative haircuts--he couldn't even picture what the woman was talking about. "Can you think of anything else at all?" he pressed.\par
Roc\'edo thought a moment. "No. That's it."\par
Just then the bed creaked loudly. Roc\'edo's client shifted his weight uncomfortably. Becker turned to him and spoke influent German. "Noch et was? Anything else? Anything to help me find the punk rocker with the ring?"\par
There was a long silence. It was as if the giant man had something he wanted to say, but he wasn't sure how to say it. His lower lip quivered momentarily, there was a pause, and then he spoke. The four words that came out were definitely English, but they were barely intelligible beneath his thick German accent. "Fock off und die."\par
Becker gaped in shock. "I beg your pardon?\par
"Fock off und die," the man repeated, patting his left palm against his fleshy right forearm--a crude approximation of the Italian gesture for "fuck you."\par
Becker was too drained to be offended. \i Fuck off and die? What happened to Das Wimp? \i0 He turned back to Roc\'edo and spoke in Spanish. "Sounds like I've overstayed my welcome."\par
"Don't worry about him." She laughed. "He's just a little frustrated. He'll get what's coming to him." She tossed her hair and winked.\par
"Is there anything else?" Becker asked. "Anything you can tell me that might help?"\par
Roc\'edo shook her head. "That's all. But you'll never find her. Seville is a big city--it can be very deceptive."\par
"I'll do the best I can." \i It's a matter of national security...\par
\i0 "If you have no luck," Roc\'edo said, eyeing the bulging envelope in Becker's pocket, "please stop back. My friend will be sleeping, no doubt. Knock quietly. I'll find us an extra room. You'll see a side of Spain you'll never forget." She pouted lusciously.\par
Becker forced a polite smile. "I should be going." He apologized to the German for interrupting his evening.\par
The giant smiled timidly. "Keine Ursache."\par
Becker headed out the door. \i No problem? Whatever happened to "Fuck off and die"?\par
