\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\kerning0\b0\fs24\par
The Commander rose through the trapdoor like Lazarus back from the dead. Despite his soggy clothes, his step was light. He strode toward Node 3--toward Susan. Toward his future.\par
The Crypto floor was again bathed in light. Freon was flowing downward through the smoldering TRANSLTR like oxygenated blood. Strathmore knew it would take a few minutes for the coolant to reach the bottom of the hull and prevent the lowest processors from igniting, but he was certain he'd acted in time. He exhaled in victory, never suspecting the truth--that it was already too late.\par
\i I'm a survivor, \i0 he thought. Ignoring the gaping hole in the Node 3 wall, he strode to the electronic doors. They hissed open. He stepped inside.\par
Susan was standing before him, damp and tousled in his blazer. She looked like a freshman coed who'd been caught in the rain. He felt like the senior who'd lent her his varsity sweater. For the first time in years, he felt young. His dream was coming true.\par
But as Strathmore moved closer, he felt he was staring into the eyes of a woman he did not recognize. Her gaze was like ice. The softness was gone. Susan Fletcher stood rigid, like an immovable statue. The only perceptible motion were the tears welling in her eyes.\par
"Susan?"\par
A single tear rolled down her quivering cheek.\par
"What is it?" the commander pleaded.\par
The puddle of blood beneath Hale's body had spread across the carpet like an oil spill. Strathmore glanced uneasily at the corpse, then back at Susan. \i Could she possibly know? \i0 There was no way. Strathmore knew he had covered every base.\par
"Susan?" he said, stepping closer. "What is it?"\par
Susan did not move.\par
"Are you worried about David?"\par
There was a slight quiver in her upper lip.\par
Strathmore stepped closer. He was going to reach for her, but he hesitated. The sound of David's name had apparently cracked the dam of grief. Slowly at first--a quiver, a tremble. And then a thundering wave of misery seemed to course through her veins. Barely able to control her shuddering lips, Susan opened her mouth to speak. Nothing came.\par
Without ever breaking the icy gaze she'd locked on Strathmore, she took her hand from the pocket of his blazer. In her hand was an object. She held it out, shaking.\par
Strathmore half expected to look down and see the Beretta leveled at his gut. But the gun was still on the floor, propped safely in Hale's hand. The object Susan was holding was smaller. Strathmore stared down at it, and an instant later, he understood.\par
As Strathmore stared, reality warped, and time slowed to a crawl. He could hear the sound of his own heart. The man who had triumphed over giants for so many years had been outdone in an instant. Slain by love--by his own foolishness. In a simple act of chivalry, he had given Susan his jacket. And with it, his SkyPager.\par
Now it was Strathmore who went rigid. Susan's hand was shaking. The pager fell at Hale's feet. With a look of astonishment and betrayal that Strathmore would never forget, Susan Fletcher raced past him out of Node 3.\par
The commander let her go. In slow motion, he bent and retrieved the pager. There were no new messages--Susan had read them all. Strathmore scrolled desperately through the list.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\qc SUBJECT: ENSEI TANKADO--TERMINATED\par
SUBJECT: PIERRE CLOUCHARDE--TERMINATED\par
SUBJECT: HANS HUBER--TERMINATED\par
SUBJECT: ROC\'cdO EVA GRANADA--TERMINATED...\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100 The list went on. Strathmore felt a wave of horror. \i I can explain!\i0  She \i will understand! Honor! Country!\i0  But there was one message he had not yet seen--one message he could never explain. Trembling, he scrolled to the final transmission.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\qc SUBJECT: DAVID BECKER--TERMINATED\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100 Strathmore hung his head. His dream was over.\par
\par
