Susan moved as if through a dream. She spun toward Jabba's keyboard. As she turned, her gaze fixed on her fianc\'e9, David Becker. Again his voice exploded overhead.\par
\i "Three! The difference between 235 and 238 is three!"\i0\par
Everyone in the room looked up.\par
\i "Three!"\i0  Susan shouted over the deafening cacophony of sirens and technicians. She pointed to the screen. All eyes followed, to Tankado's hand, outstretched, three fingers waving desperately in the Sevillian sun.\par
Jabba went rigid. "Oh my God!" He suddenly realized the crippled genius had been giving them the answer all the time.\par
"Three's prime!" Soshi blurted. "Three's a \i prime\i0  number!"\par
Fontaine looked dazed. "Can it be that simple?"\par
\i "Outbound data!"\i0  a technician cried. \i "It's going fast!"\i0\par
Everyone on the podium dove for the terminal at the same instant--a mass of outstretched hands. But through the crowd, Susan, like a shortstop stabbing a line drive, connected with her target. She typed the number 3. Everyone wheeled to the wall screen. Above the chaos, it simply read.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\qc ENTER PASS-KEY? 3\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100 "Yes!" Fontaine commanded. "Do it now!"\par
Susan held her breath and lowered her finger on the ENTER key. The computer beeped once.\par
Nobody moved.\par
Three agonizing seconds later, nothing had happened.\par
The sirens kept going. Five seconds. Six seconds.\par
\i "Outbound data!"\i0\par
\i "No change!"\i0\par
Suddenly Midge began pointing wildly to the screen above. "Look!"\par
On it, a message had materialized.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\qc KILL CODE CONFIRMED.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100 "Upload the firewalls!" Jabba ordered.\par
But Soshi was a step ahead of him. She had already sent the command.\par
\i "Outbound interrupt!"\i0  a technician yelled.\par
\i "Tie-ins severed!"\i0\par
On the VR overhead, the first of the five firewalls began reappearing. The black lines attacking the core were instantly severed.\par
"Reinstating!" Jabba cried. "The damn thing's reinstating!"\par
There was a moment of tentative disbelief, as if at any instant, everything would fall apart. But then the second firewall began reappearing... and then the third. Moments later the entire series of filters reappeared. The databank was secure.\par
The room erupted. Pandemonium. Technicians hugged, tossing computer printouts in the air in celebration. Sirens wound down. Brinkerhoff grabbed Midge and held on. Soshi burst into tears.\par
"Jabba," Fontaine demanded. "How much did they get?"\par
"Very little," Jabba said, studying his monitor. "Very little. And nothing complete."\par
Fontaine nodded slowly, a wry smile forming in the corner of his mouth. He looked around for Susan Fletcher, but she was already walking toward the front of the room. On the wall before her, David Becker's face filled the screen.\par
"David?"\par
"Hey, gorgeous." He smiled.\par
"Come home," she said. "Come home, right now."\par
"Meet you at Stone Manor?" he asked.\par
She nodded, the tears welling. "Deal."\par
"Agent Smith?" Fontaine called.\par
Smith appeared onscreen behind Becker. "Yes, sir?"\par
"It appears Mr. Becker has a date. Could you see that he gets home immediately?"\par
Smith nodded. "Our jet's in M\'e1laga." He patted Becker on the back. "You're in for a treat, Professor. Ever flown in a Learjet 60?"\par
Becker chuckled. "Not since yesterday."\par
