When Susan awoke, the sun was shining. the soft rays sifted through the curtains and filtered across her goosedown feather bed. She reached for David. \i Am I dreaming? \i0 Her body remained motionless, spent, still dizzy from the night before.\par
"David?" She moaned.\par
There was no reply. She opened her eyes, her skin still tingling. The mattress on the other side of the bed was cold. David was gone.\par
\i I'm dreaming, \i0 Susan thought. She sat up. The room was Victorian, all lace and antiques--Stone Manor's finest suite. Her overnight bag was in the middle of the hardwood floor... her lingerie on a Queen Anne chair beside the bed.\par
Had David really arrived? She had memories--his body against hers, his waking her with soft kisses. Had she dreamed it all? She turned to the bedside table. There was an empty bottle of champagne, two glasses... and a note.\par
Rubbing the sleep from her eyes, Susan drew the comforter around her naked body and read the message.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100\qc Dearest Susan,\par
I love you.\par
Without wax, David.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\sb100\sa100 She beamed and pulled the note to her chest. It was David, all right. \i Without wax... \i0 it was the one code she had yet to break.\par
Something stirred in the corner, and Susan looked up. On a plush divan, basking in the morning sun, wrapped in thick bathrobe, David Becker sat quietly watching her. She reached out, beckoning him to come to her.\par
"Without wax?" she cooed, taking him in her arms.\par
"Without wax." He smiled.\par
She kissed him deeply. "Tell me what it means."\par
"No chance." He laughed. "A couple needs secrets--it keeps things interesting."\par
Susan smiled coyly. "Any more interesting than last night and I'll never walk again."\par
David took her in his arms. He felt weightless. He had almost died yesterday, and yet here he was, as alive as he had ever felt in his life.\par
Susan lay with her head on his chest, listening to the beat of his heart. She couldn't believe that she had thought he was gone forever.\par
"David." She sighed, eyeing the note beside the table. "Tell me about 'without wax.' You know I hate codes I can't break."\par
David was silent.\par
"Tell me." Susan pouted. "Or you'll never have me again."\par
"Liar."\par
Susan hit him with a pillow. "Tell me! Now!"\par
But David knew he would never tell. The secret behind "without wax" was too sweet. Its origins were ancient. During the Renaissance, Spanish sculptors who made mistakes while carving expensive marble often patched their flaws with \i cera\i0 --"wax." A statue that had no flaws and required no patching was hailed as a "sculpture \i sincera"\i0  or a "sculpture without wax." The phrase eventually came to mean anything honest or true. The English word "sincere" evolved from the Spanish \i sincera\i0 --"without wax." David's secret code was no great mystery--he was simply signing his letters "Sincerely." Somehow he suspected Susan would not be amused.\par
"You'll be pleased to know," David said, attempting to change the subject, "that during the flight home, I called the president of the university."\par
Susan looked up, hopeful. "Tell me you resigned as department chair."\par
David nodded. "I'll be back in the classroom next semester."\par
She sighed in relief. "Right where you belonged in the first place."\par
David smiled softly. "Yeah, I guess Spain reminded me what's important."\par
"Back to breaking coeds' hearts?" Susan kissed his cheek. "Well, at least you'll have time to help me edit my manuscript."\par
"Manuscript?"\par
"Yes. I've decided to publish."\par
"Publish?" David looked doubtful. "Publish \i what?"\par
\i0 "Some ideas I have on variant filter protocols and quadratic residues."\par
He groaned. "Sounds like a real best-seller."\par
She laughed. "You'd be surprised."\par
David fished inside the pocket of his bathrobe and pulled out a small object. "Close your eyes. I have something for you."\par
Susan closed her eyes. "Let me guess--a gaudy gold ring with Latin all over it?"\par
"No." David chuckled. "I had Fontaine return that to Ensei Tankado's estate." He took Susan's hand and slipped something onto her finger.\par
"Liar." Susan laughed, opening her eyes. "I knew--"\par
But Susan stopped short. The ring on her finger was not Tankado's at all. It was a platinum setting that held a glittering diamond solitaire.\par
Susan gasped.\par
David looked her in the eye. "Will you marry me?"\par
Susan's breath caught in her throat. She looked at him and then back to the ring. Her eyes suddenly welled up. "Oh, David... I don't know what to say."\par
"Say yes."\par
Susan turned away and didn't say a word.\par
David waited. "Susan Fletcher, I love you. Marry me."\par
Susan lifted her head. Her eyes were filled with tears. "I'm sorry, David," she whispered. "I... I can't."\par
David stared in shock. He searched her eyes for the playful glimmer he'd come to expect from her. It wasn't there. "S-Susan," he stammered. "I--I don't understand."\par
"I can't," she repeated. "I can't marry you." She turned away. Her shoulders started trembling. She covered her face with her hands.\par
David was bewildered. "But, Susan... I thought..." He held her trembling shoulders and turned her body toward him. It was then that he understood. Susan Fletcher was not crying at all; she was in hysterics.\par
"I won't marry you!" She laughed, attacking again with the pillow. "Not until you explain 'without wax'! You're driving me \i crazy!"\i0\par
